<br>
The Death Penalty is no more a deterrent to future crimes than life sentences.  The punishment in a crime of this severity is not going to affect the statistics.  Someone who has made a conscious decision to kill someone is beyond worrying about what may happen to him if he's caught.  If he's concerned about it, he simply will not commit the crime.  In the case of an 'accidental' shooting (ie, someone robbing a store and shooting the clerk) isn't given time to make a decision about a killing, they simply react to whatever happens which causes them to pull the trigger.  In one case you have someone beyond caring what happens if he gets caught (as he's convinced he won't be) and in the other, you have someone who never truly intended to shoot someone, and therefore never considered the consequences.  (side note- this obiviously assumes in both cases the individual is monumentally stupid- which murdering someone and robbing a store with a loaded gun without intending to use it, makes you)  In short, the consequences never enter the planning stage, therefore, will not deter the person from commiting the act.  The person who does NOT act on their desire isn't afraid of the punishment, they're afraid of being caught (as has been stated already).<br>
<br>
Now...  to the system itself.  We all know the system is flawed, but it's a question of if it's chronically flawed or simply imperfect.  It's all well and good saying there's something wrong, but unless you can actively offer a suggestion for change, pointing at something and yelling 'it's broke' doesn't repair it.  The legal system should be revamped in some way, but I won't pretend to have the answers.  For now we must support the system in place until we have the technology or the moral ability to remove the possibility of deciet.  So long as man CAN lie, he will lie, is my opinion.  And so long as we have a system of determining guilt which involves people getting paid, everyone involved will do whatever they must to win.  If a defense attorney makes more money by the more people he is able to get a jury to say 'innocent' to, you can rest assured that attorney will skirt the law and moralily for as long as he can to the Nth degree.  <br>
<br>
Now, that's a buncha paragraphs stating the blindingly obvious.  Here's my opinion- Until and unless the system can be made flawless, we must trust percentages.  There will always be a chance someone who is innocent will be convicted of a crime, and this is simply part of the statistics in my opinion.  People who commit violent crimes deserve to be removed from society, and from the standpoint of expense, death will always be cheaper.  (And I've seen statistics which claim killing someone is more expensive than keeping them in prison for life...  and I beg of you, don't spout them back at me- there is nothing you'll ever show me which makes me believe that)  Killing someone for murder is punishment, plain and simple, and nothing more.  It will not stop someone else from commiting a similar crime.  So, for now, if we have no way to remove the possibility of an innocent person being put to death for a crime he didn't commit, then I say that's a risk we're all going to have to take.  Better that than to suggest a serial killer or murderer of children should be fed, clothed, and housed on my hard earned tax dollar.<br>
<br>
EDIT- I'd be responding, but the little 'Add Reply' button seems to have suddenly dissapeared... /tap tap tap<br>
<br>
Hopefully, you look up here, cause I can't seem to reply anymore...  Anyway, yes, essentially that's what I'm saying- it's not the fear of death which stops someone from commiting Murder.  Look at the numbers, Murders happen more frequently in states with death penalties as in states which have no death penalty.  It's not the fear of the punishment, it's the fear of getting caught.  <br>
<br>
Once you have made a conscious decision to kill another human being, you're beyond consequences, and likely fully convinced you're going to get away with it.  The punishment is not the deterrent, it's the possibility of not getting away with it.  Honestly, is there any difference between Death and Life in Prison?  Personally, I'd see a life sentence as a FAR worse punishment, but that is neither here nor there.  My point here is I support the death penalty insofar as a solution to prison overcrowding, but do not agree with it as a deterrent to future crimes (unless of course, you're talking about the condemned, he certainly won't be commiting any more).  <br>
<br>
But anyway, it's my opinion, not trying to make it yours <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/usespetoxri.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sespetoxri</A> at: 6/5/02 6:22:03 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/umorkenlar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Morkenlar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Councilman</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/5/02 5:33:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/finfinitusvindicatfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=28.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Capital Punishment</span><hr size=1> &quot;The Death Penalty is no more a deterrent to future crimes than life sentences. &quot;<br>
